initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: This phenomenon can be attributed to the fact that quantum convolutional neural networks (QCNNS) are less prone to overfitting due to their inherent ability to reduce the dimensionality of the input data, which in turn, reduces the risk of overfitting.
Additionally, QCNNS have been shown to be more robust to noisy data and outliers, which is particularly important in many real-world applications where data is often imperfect.

This is because QCNNS are capable of learning robust features that are less sensitive to noisy or missing values, allowing them to generalize better to unseen data and improve overall model performance.
In contrast, traditional neural networks can be heavily influenced by noisy or missing values, which can lead to overfitting and poor generalization to new data.
This is particularly problematic in real-world applications, where data is often imperfect and incomplete, and where the goal is to make accurate predictions on unseen data.
Additionally, the reliance on perfect or complete data can lead to overfitting, which is when a model becomes too specialized to the training data and fails to generalize well to new, unseen data.
This can result in poor performance on the validation set and ultimately, the model's ability to make accurate predictions on new data is compromised.

This is because the model is overfitting to the training data, meaning it is becoming too specialized to fit the noise and random fluctuations in the training data rather than learning the underlying patterns and relationships.
As a result, when the model is tested on new, unseen data, it performs poorly due to its inability to generalize well beyond the training data.
This is a common issue known as overfitting, which occurs when a model is too complex and is able to memorize the training data rather than learning the underlying patterns and relationships.
As a result, the model's performance on the training data is excellent, but it fails to generalize well to new, unseen data, leading to poor performance on the test set.

This is a classic case of overfitting, where the model is too specialized to the training data and does not capture the underlying patterns and relationships that are present in the broader data distribution.

In other words, the model is learning the noise and idiosyncrasies of the training data rather than generalizing to new, unseen data, which can lead to poor performance when evaluated on test or unseen data.
This phenomenon is often referred to as overfitting, and it's a common challenge in machine learning, particularly when the training dataset is small or noisy.

One way to mitigate overfitting is to use techniques such as regularization, which adds a penalty term to the loss function to discourage complex models. Another approach is to use early stopping, where the training process is halted when the model's performance on the validation set starts to degrade.

A third approach is to use data augmentation, which involves artificially increasing the size of the training set by applying random transformations to the existing data. This can help the model learn to generalize better by reducing its reliance on specific features or patterns.
For example, in the case of images, data augmentation can involve rotating, flipping, or zooming the images, as well as adjusting the brightness, contrast, and saturation.
These types of transformations can help to increase the size of the training dataset, reduce overfitting, and improve the robustness of the model to minor variations in the input data.

By artificially augmenting the dataset, we can expose the model to a wider range of scenarios and edge cases, allowing it to learn more generalizable patterns and become less susceptible to overfitting and poor performance on unseen data.

This approach can also help to identify and rectify biases in the model's decision-making process, as the artificially augmented data may highlight areas where the model is prone to making incorrect or unfair judgments.
